SIMPLE: portrait
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Portrait
<hw>Por"trait</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[F., originally p.
p. of <ets>portraire</ets> to portray. See <er>Portray</er>.]</ety>
<sn>1.</sn> <def>The likeness of a person, painted, drawn, or engraved;
commonly, a representation of the human face painted from real
life.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>In <qex>portraits</qex>, the grace, and, we may add, the likeness,
consists more in the general air than in the exact similitude of every
feature.</q> <rj><qau>Sir J. Reynolds.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ The meaning of the word is sometimes extended so as to
include a photographic likeness.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Hence, any graphic or vivid delineation or
description of a person; <as>as, a <ex>portrait</ex> in
words</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><mcol><col><b>Portrait bust</b></col>, <it>or</it>
<col><b>Portrait statue</b></col></mcol>, <cd>a bust or statue
representing the actual features or person of an individual; -- in
distinction from an <xex>ideal bust</xex> or
<xex>statue</xex>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Portrait</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Portrait
<hw>Por"trait</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <def>To portray; to draw.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Spenser.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Portraitist</ent>⟦br⟧
